            <h2 class="title"><a href="/node/109">Upcoming 2015 Events</a></h2>
          
  <div class="content"><ul>
<li>Martin Luther King Jr. Day Celebration
<ul>
<li>11 a.m. Jan. 19, Tippecanoe County Public Library, 627 South St.</li>
<li>Local resident Tom Brown will explore King’s 1967 speech, &ldquo;Beyond Vietnam,&rdquo; which denounced America&apos;s war in Vietnam.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Conversation Circles
<ul>
<li>The community-building arm of the Diversity Roundtable is holding its January call-out from 6 to 8 p.m. Jan. 27 at the downtown library branch.</li>
<li>The call-out is open to anyone who is interested in learning more about the circles, which aim to foster a better sense of community through respectful listening and sharing of diverse experiences.</li>
<li>A training session on Conversation Circle facilitation also will be offered Jan. 18. For more information on this session, email drtconversationcircles (at) gmail.com.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Congress Street United Methodist Church programs
<ul>
<li>Last fall, the church organized a communitywide discussion series based on the book, “The New Jim Crow: Mass Incarceration in the Age of Colorblindness.”</li>
<li>It plans on having another discussion series on race at the end of February.</li>
<li>Organizers are considering books that explore the concept of &rdquo;white privilege.&ldquo;</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>1 in 4 Campaign
<ul>
<li>Michael Oxenrider, director of education and marketing for Mental Health America of Tippecanoe, is recruiting community members for a photography project that shows 1 in 4 people is affected by mental illness.</li>
<li>If interested, call Oxenrider at 765-742-1800.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
